"Anisimov O.A., Nelson F.E.","Permafrost distribution in the northern hemisphere under scenarios of climatic change",1996,"Global and Planetary Change","14","1-2",,"59","72",,,10.1016/0921-8181(96)00002-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030201278&partnerID=40&md5=ab9c2f7be1a5ba97cd65d327d17cc9ed","Department of Climatology, State Hydrological Institute, St. Petersburg, Russian Federation; Department of Geography, State Univ. of New York at Albany, Albany, NY, United States","Anisimov, O.A., Department of Climatology, State Hydrological Institute, St. Petersburg, Russian Federation; Nelson, F.E., Department of Geography, State Univ. of New York at Albany, Albany, NY, United States","The proportion of the Earth's land area underlain by permafrost, currently about 25%, is expected to contract substantially in response to climatic warming. Maps of permafrost distribution in the northern hemisphere were generated using three general circulation models and an empirical paleoreconstruction, all scaled to a 2°C global warming, in conjunction with a permafrost model that has successfully replicated the arrangement of contemporary permafrost zones in several high-latitude regions. The simulations indicate a 25-44% reduction in the total area occupied by equilibrium permafrost. Conditions specified by the climate models result in a poleward (north-northeast) displacement of all permafrost zones. The continuous permafrost zone was most severely impacted in the simulations, with reductions in its areal extent ranging from 29% to 67%. The permafrost model was also used to hindcast the distribution of permafrost in Russia during the Holocene climatic optimum and Eemian interglacial. Agreement of modeled results with mappings based on independent criteria confirm the model's effectiveness.",,"climate change; permafrost; permafrost distribution; Northern Hemisphere",,,,,,"Anisimov, O.A., Changing climate and permafrost distribution in the Soviet Arctic (1989) Phys. Geogr., 10 (3), pp. 285-293; Anisimov, O.A., Nelson, F.E., Application of mathematical models to investigation of the climate-permafrost coupling (1990) Meteorol. Gidrol., 1990 (10), pp. 13-20. , in Russian; English translation appears as ""Application of mathematical models to investigate the interaction between the climate and permafrost"", Sov. Meteorol. Hydrol., 1990(10): 8-13; Anisimov, O.A., Nelson, F.E., Permafrost Distribution and Climatic Change: Results from Transient General Circulation Models; Glossary of permafrost and related groundice terms (1988) Natl. Res. Counc. Can. Tech. Mem., 142. , 156 pp; Boardman, J., (1987) Periglacial Processes and Landforms in Britain and Ireland, , Cambridge Univ. Press, 296 pp; Bromwich, D.H., Tzeng, R.-Y., Parish, T.R., Simulation of the modern Arctic climate by the NCAR CCMI (1994) J. Clim., 7 (7), pp. 1050-1069; Brown, J., A circumarctic map of permafrost and ground ice conditions (1992) Proc. 1st Int. Conf. Cryopedol., pp. 15-21. , D.A. Gilichinsky (Editor), Pushino Res. Centre, Pushino; Budyko, M.I., Izrael, Y.A., (1987) Anthropogenic Climatic Change, , Hydrometeoizdat, Leningrad, 405 pp. (in Russian; English edition published by Univ. Ariz. Press, 1992); Budyko, M.I., Yefimova, N.A., Lokshina, I.Y., Anticipated modifications of global climate (1989) Izv. Akad. Nauk SSSR, Ser. Geogr., 1989 (5), pp. 45-55. , in Russian; English translation in Sov. Geogr., 31(1): 11-24, 1990; Budyko, M.I., Borzenkova, I.I., Menzhulin, G.V., Seljakov, K.I., On pending changes of the global climate (1992) Izv. Ross. Akad. Nauk, Ser. Geogr., 4, pp. 36-52. , in Russian; Burn, C.R., Permafrost tectonics, and past and future regional climate change, Yukon and adjacent Northwest Territories (1994) Can. J. Earth Sci., 31 (1), pp. 182-191; Cess, R.D., Potter, G.L., A methodology for understanding and intercomparing atmospheric climate feedback processes within general circulation models (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93, pp. 8305-8314; Cess, R.D